1 10. Rulemaking. The bureau may adopt routine technical rules as defined in Title 5,
2 chapter 375, subchapter 2‑A to administer this section.
3 Sec. 2. 28-A MRSA §1358 is enacted to read:
4 §1358. Unlicensed manufacture
5 A license for the manufacture of homemade liquor is not required under this Title if
6 the conditions prescribed in this section are met. For purposes of this section, "homemade
7 liquor" has the same meaning as in section 1057, subsection 1, paragraph A.
8 1. Permitted liquor judging competition events. Homemade liquor may be removed
9 from the premises where the homemade liquor was made if the homemade liquor is entered
10 into a permitted liquor judging competition event as provided in section 1057.
11 2. Prohibition on added spirits. Homemade liquor may not contain added spirits.
12 3. Prohibition on sale. Homemade liquor may not be sold or offered for sale.
13 4. Violation. A violation of this section is a Class E crime.'
14 Amend the bill by relettering or renumbering any nonconsecutive Part letter or section
15 number to read consecutively.
16 SUMMARY
1177 This amendment replaces the bill and authorizes one or more certificate of approval
1188 holders that are manufacturers to apply for a permit to host a liquor judging competition
1199 event subject to conditions. The amendment provides that a certificate of approval holder
2200 issued a liquor judging competition event permit may charge a fee for participation in a
2211 competition event and the competition event is not required to occur on premises licensed
2222 by the Department of Administrative and Financial Services, Bureau of Alcoholic
2233 Beverages and Lottery Operations.
24 The amendment also specifies that only judges and stewards may taste liquor entries
25 in a liquor judging competition event; homemade spirits may not be entered into a liquor
26 judging competition event; and liquor may not be sold or offered for sale at a liquor judging
27 competition event.
28 The amendment authorizes the bureau to adopt rules to administer the law regulating
29 liquor judging competition events. The amendment also defines "homemade liquor" to
30 mean malt liquor, wine or hard cider made by a person's own efforts in the person's home
31 for personal use that is not offered for sale and that does not contain added spirits.
